04242nam a22005775i 9780520918412DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19931993cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209184127 a10.1525/97805209184122doi  a(DE-B1597)648585  a(OCoLC)44956888  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aDC59.8.U6bK85 1996 7aHIS0100002bisacsh04a944.0831 aKuisel, Richard F., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSeducing the French :bThe Dilemma of Americanization /cRichard F. Kuisel; ed. by Richard F. Kuisel. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[1993] 4c©1993  a1 online resource (293 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPREFACE -- t1 Anti-Americanism and National Identity -- t2 The New American Hegemony -- t3 Yankee Go Home -- t4 The Missionaries of the Marshall Plan -- t5 The American Temptation -- t6 The Gaullist Exorcism -- t7 The American Challenge -- t8 Détente -- t9 Vive l'Amérique -- t10 Reflections -- tNOTES -- tSELECT BIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen Coca-Cola was introduced in France in the late 1940s, the country's most prestigious newspaper warned that Coke threatened France's cultural landscape. This is one of the examples cited in Richard Kuisel's engaging exploration of France's response to American influence after World War II. In analyzing early French resistance and then the gradual adaptation to all things American that evolved by the mid-1980s, he offers an intriguing study of national identity and the protection of cultural boundaries.The French have historically struggled against Americanization in order to safeguard "Frenchness." What would happen to the French way of life if gaining American prosperity brought vulgar materialism and social conformity? A clash between American consumerism and French civilisation seemed inevitable.Cold War anti-Communism, the Marshall Plan, the Coca-Cola controversy, and de Gaulle's efforts to curb American investment illustrate ways that anti-Americanization was played out. Kuisel also raises issues that extend beyond France, including the economic, social, and cultural effects of the Americanized consumer society that have become a global phenomenon.Kuisel's lively account reaches across French society to include politicians, businessmen, trade unionists, Parisian intelligentsia, and ordinary citizens. The result reveals much about the French—and about Americans. As Euro Disney welcomes travellers to its Parisian fantasyland, and with French recently declared the official language of France (to defend it from the encroachments of English), Kuisel's book is especially relevant.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPublic opinionzFrance. 4aEurope. 4aGeneral. 4aHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh1 aKuisel, Richard F., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052020698440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052091841240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520918412423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520918412/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles